The paper discusses an algorithm for propagating evidence through belief networks, which is a common topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The algorithm involves examining a subset of nodes in the network, which suggests a focus on efficient computation and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also mentions the "anytime" property of the algorithm, which is a concept often studied in the field of search and optimization (cs.SI). Finally, the use of interval bounds on marginal probabilities suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT).
